import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());

        int n = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
        int m = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

        long[] arr = new long[n];

        st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            arr[i] = Long.parseLong(st.nextToken());
        }

        long[] diff = new long[n + 2];

        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
            int l = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
            int r = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

            diff[l]++;
            diff[r + 1]--;
        }

        long[] counts = new long[n];
        long current = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            current += diff[i];
            counts[i - 1] = current;
        }

        Arrays.sort(arr);
        Arrays.sort(counts);

        long total = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            total += arr[i] * counts[i];
        }

        System.out.println(total);
    }
}


🔴 Why Scanner Is Slow

When you write:

Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
int n = sc.nextInt();
Internally Scanner:

Reads input

Uses regex parsing

Splits tokens

Converts to integer

Does safety checks

👉 That regex parsing makes it slow.

For small input → OK
For 200,000+ numbers → TLE

🟢 What BufferedReader Does
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
BufferedReader:

Reads a full line at once

Stores it in memory buffer

Does NOT parse anything

Very minimal overhead

It is just a fast raw reader.

Example:

String line = br.readLine();

This reads the whole line as a string.

Fast.

🔵 Then What Is StringTokenizer?

After reading a full line:

String line = "200000 200000";

We need to split it into numbers.

Instead of using:

line.split(" ")

(which uses regex → slow)

We use:

StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(line);

Then:

int n = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
int m = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

StringTokenizer is much faster because:

No regex

Just splits by space

Lightweight

⚡ Speed Comparison
Method	Speed
Scanner	Slow
split()	Medium
BufferedReader + StringTokenizer	Fast


🔹 Suppose Input Is:
5 3
10 20 30 40 50
1 3
2 4
1 5
🔹 Step 1
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
What is in br?

br does not store the input.

It is just a reader object connected to standard input (keyboard).

Think of it as:

📥 A pipe that can read lines from input.

It waits until you call:

br.readLine()
🔹 Step 2
StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
What happens here?

br.readLine() reads the first full line:

"5 3"

That string is passed to StringTokenizer

So now:

st contains tokens: ["5", "3"]

It splits the string by spaces.

🔹 Step 3
int n = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

st.nextToken() returns:

"5"

Now:

n = 5

Remaining tokens in st:

["3"]
🔹 Step 4
int m = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

st.nextToken() returns:

"3"

Now:

m = 3

Now st is empty (no tokens left).

🔹 Step 5
st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());

Now br.readLine() reads second line:

"10 20 30 40 50"

So now:

st contains: ["10", "20", "30", "40", "50"]
🔹 Step 6 (Inside Loop)
arr[i] = Long.parseLong(st.nextToken());

Each time nextToken() is called:

Call	Returned	Remaining tokens
1	"10"	["20","30","40","50"]
2	"20"	["30","40","50"]
3	"30"	["40","50"]
4	"40"	["50"]
5	"50"	[]

After loop, st is empty again.

🔹 Step 7 (Reading Queries)

Inside:

st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());

Each time it reads a new query line.

First Query

br.readLine() reads:

"1 3"

Now:

st = ["1", "3"]

Then:

int l = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken()); // "1"
int r = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken()); // "3"

Now st is empty again.

Second Query

br.readLine() reads:

"2 4"

Now:

st = ["2", "4"]

After nextToken() twice → empty again.

🔥 Final Understanding
br:

It does NOT store all input.

It reads one full line when readLine() is called.

Returns that line as a String.

st:

Stores tokens of only one line at a time.

Splits line into pieces separated by space.

nextToken() gives next piece.

🧠 Visual Flow
Input → br.readLine() → String line
String line → StringTokenizer → tokens
tokens → nextToken() → individual numbers
⚡ Why Not Use Scanner?

Scanner is slower because:

It does parsing internally

More overhead

BufferedReader + StringTokenizer is much faster for competitive programming.

